.TH CSVI 1 "June 2025" "csvi" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
csvi \- terminal CSV viewer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B csvi
[\fIOPTIONS\fR]
.I FILE
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B csvi
opens a CSV file in an interactive terminal viewer. Navigate with arrow keys,
page keys, and Home/End. Press Esc to enter command mode.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-separator= \fICHAR\fR
Cell separator character (default: ;).
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-verbose
Write diagnostic messages to stderr.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Print usage and exit.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-version
Print version and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
Press Esc, then type:
.TP
.B :q
Quit.
.TP
.BI : N
Go to line \fIN\fR (1-based input, converted internally).
.TP
.BI :c N
Go to column \fIN\fR.
.TP
.BI : Nx M
Go to column \fIN\fR, line \fIM\fR.
.TP
.B :0 / :-1
First / last line.
.TP
.B :c0 / :c-1
First / last column.
.PP
See Commands.md in the source tree for the full list.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
General error.
.TP
.B 2
Usage error.
.TP
.B 3
I/O error (file not found or unreadable).
.SH FILES
.I FILE
CSV file to display.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR less (1)
